<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE-SUICIDES</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 20 22:58:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
TO Gerald:<br>
    The data I state comes from a combination of sources, the most recent of it comes from the VA.  I too work with Vets, God Bless Them and the rate of suicide among Vets now is supposed to be lower than ever before due to the time elapsed from the traumatic period of service.  According to a good friend of mine who is a Psychologist and counselor, who works with vets, especially the elderly ones (World War II) the highest suicide rate among vets is among the ailing, elderly vets of World War II.  Her data comes from claims and studies made from proven, qualified vets from the Veterans Administration.  There is no doubt, Vietnam Vets are still killing themselves,  but we have to remember that a lot of vets have helped their brothers, as is obvious of that you too help.  This help has aided many vets to start on the road to healing.  We have to remember that some vets today may kill themselves for reasons other than trauma.  There has been 30 more years of life since then.  No Vet should have to kill himself.  All I am saying is that based on genuine, proven statistical data from the CDC, the VA, and the state health Dept of Wisconsin, it is not possible that 30,000 or more vets have killed themselves and certainly not 50,000 vets or more.  Those of us, thay help just see the effects and its more personal to us.  Thanks for listening and let's hope it's a better year for all those that served this country.<br>
                 
<p><code>--   (Joe) </code><p>


